{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563486"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T22:59:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T22:59:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16767"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16767"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.73,0.04,0,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9458"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67294"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9458"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16767"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52746"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4302"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"9009"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22347"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30651"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43660"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48775"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67294"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of her fingers turning white and then blue when exposed to cold temperatures. The episodes last approximately 15 minutes and resolve with warming. She works as a barista and notices the symptoms particularly when handling cold drinks or when walking to work in winter. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She smokes five cigarettes per day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her hands are warm and well-perfused with normal capillary refill. There are no skin changes, ulcers, or joint swelling. Nail fold capillaroscopy is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous prostaglandins","Lifestyle modification advice","Low-dose aspirin","Surgical sympathectomy","Calcium channel blocker therapy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of primary Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon, characterised by episodic digital vasospasm triggered by cold exposure. The symmetrical involvement, young age, female gender, and absence of underlying connective tissue disease features are typical. The normal nail fold capillaroscopy helps confirm the primary nature of the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELifestyle modification advice\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line management. This includes avoiding cold exposure (wearing gloves, using hand warmers), smoking cessation, and avoiding vasoconstrictive medications. These measures are often sufficient to control symptoms in mild cases of primary Raynaud\u0027s.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium channel blocker therapy\u003C/strong\u003E with medications such as nifedipine is typically reserved for patients who have failed lifestyle modifications or have more severe symptoms. While effective, it should not be first-line therapy given the potential for side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical sympathectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely performed and is reserved for severe, refractory cases with digital ulceration or gangrene, which are more commonly seen in secondary Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow-dose aspirin\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely recommended for primary Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon as there is limited evidence for its effectiveness. It may be considered in secondary Raynaud\u0027s associated with systemic sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous prostaglandins\u003C/strong\u003E are used only in severe cases of secondary Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon with critical digital ischaemia, which is not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon typically affects young women and involves symmetrical vasospasm of fingers and toes.","Cold exposure and emotional stress are common triggers for Raynaud\u0027s attacks.","Lifestyle modifications including avoiding cold exposure and smoking cessation are first-line management for Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne, VIC: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2023. Available at: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/","Howard JE, Patterson J, Dalton JA, et al. Behaviour change interventions for the management of Raynaud\u2019s phenomenon: a systematic literature review. BMJ Open. 2017;7(11):e017039. doi:10.1136/bmjopen-2017-017039."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52746"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16767"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52746"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T19:13:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T19:14:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9458"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67294"}}},"meta":{"ca